Scan 1	Nmap + Netcat	Basic subnet scanning
Scan 2	Nmap + Netcat	Advanced network reconnaissance
üíª Technical Implementation
Basic Network Communication
bash
# Connect to TCP service
nc 10.0.0.2 31337

# Send data to service
echo "Hello, World!" | nc 10.0.0.2 31337

# Listen for incoming connections
nc -l -p 31337
Network Scanning
bash
# Basic port scan on /24 subnet
nmap -p 31337 10.0.0.0/24 -Pn --open

# Aggressive scan on larger subnet
nmap -p 31337 10.0.0.0/18 -n -Pn --open -T5 --min-rate 5000 --max-retries 0

# Connect to discovered services
nc -nv 10.0.0.224 31337
nc -nv 10.0.170.2 31337
Advanced Nmap Techniques
bash
# Greppable output for automation
nmap -p 31337 10.0.0.0/18 -oG - | grep '/open/'

# Optimized scanning parameters
-T5          # Timing template (insane speed)
--min-rate 5000  # Minimum packets per second
--max-retries 0  # No retransmissions for speed
-Pn          # No host discovery (treat all hosts as up)
üîê Security Insights
Port 31337 is commonly associated with "elite" or backdoor services

Network segmentation (different subnets) requires broader scanning strategies

Service discovery is the first step in network penetration testing

Scan timing optimization balances speed against detection risk

Raw socket communication demonstrates the foundation of all network services

Large-scale scanning requires efficient tools and methodologies

üéØ Key Techniques Mastered
Netcat Proficiency: Using nc for both client and server roles

Subnet Calculation: Understanding CIDR notation and IP ranges

Service Discovery: Identifying open ports and available services

Scan Optimization: Balancing speed, accuracy, and network impact

Network Protocol Understanding: TCP handshakes and connection lifecycle

Enterprise Reconnaissance: Techniques for large network environments

